The paper proposes a framework for generating adversarial text, which is a natural language processing (NLP) task. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also uses autoencoders and optimization techniques, which are common in machine learning and deep learning, suggesting cs.LG (Machine Learning) as the second likely sub-category. The paper also involves targeted attacks, which is a common topic in adversarial machine learning, indicating cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as the third likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the robustness of NLP models, which is a security-related topic, making cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) the fourth likely sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions image and audio adversarial examples, which are related to computer vision, indicating cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) as the fifth likely sub-category.
